# ZigbeeLens Home Assistant integration (HACS)

Read-only Home Assistant bridge to
[ZigbeeLens Core](https://github.com/@SOURCE_REPOSITORY@).

## Prerequisites

**ZigbeeLens Core must already be running.** This integration does not collect Zigbee2MQTT data directly.

Requires Home Assistant **2025.1.0 or newer**.

## Release status — local/staged integration only

**Public HACS installation is unavailable for this reviewed package.** The
reviewed public `@REVIEWED_HACS_REPOSITORY@` satellite is not synchronized with
this stage and must not be used to validate it. Synchronization and publication
require a separate explicitly authorized task. Docker/Compose is the current
portable Core deployment route.

Reviewed public-satellite state (historical evidence):

- repository: `@REVIEWED_HACS_REPOSITORY@`
- commit: `050d118b3e1406343255594fe64cd569e2420888`
- reviewed: `2026-07-23`

At that commit, the public satellite advertised version `0.1.13`. The reviewed
materially different candidate stage now uses the previously unused version
`@VERSION@`, which uniquely identifies that stage. The satellite is not assumed
to remain at that commit. Re-check its current tree before publication, then
make the staged and intended satellite trees identical while preserving a
version that uniquely identifies that tree.

The staged package owns durable polling options, fail-closed compatibility,
distinct Decision payload repair guidance, declarative/runtime single-entry
ownership, exact HA compatibility lanes, and generated official-validation
workflows. Public installation remains unavailable until the staged and
satellite trees/version are synchronized, the generated exact HA and official
HACS/hassfest jobs pass remotely on that tree, and publication is explicitly
authorized. Local structural validation does not close those remote gates.

Run Core using one of:

- **Docker** — `ghcr.io/@SOURCE_REPOSITORY@` (see source-revision
  [docs/docker.md](https://github.com/@SOURCE_REPOSITORY@/blob/@SOURCE_COMMIT@/docs/docker.md))
- Another Core deployment with an HTTP(S) origin reachable from Home Assistant

## Local staged integration testing

### Package provenance

Package source commit:
[`@SOURCE_COMMIT@`](https://github.com/@SOURCE_REPOSITORY@/commit/@SOURCE_COMMIT@).
The generated `SOURCE_COMMIT` file records the same commit. Package
documentation is pinned to
[docs/hacs.md](https://github.com/@SOURCE_REPOSITORY@/blob/@SOURCE_COMMIT@/docs/hacs.md)
at that exact source revision. The Docker prerequisite above is pinned to the
same source revision for the Core image-channel and installation contract.

The packager requires clean package inputs, rejects an unverifiable or
different-from-HEAD source override, and reads the stage from the selected HEAD
Git tree.

This README belongs to the tree generated by
`./scripts/package-hacs-repo.sh`. Validate the stage from the monorepo with
`bash dist/zigbeelens-hacs/scripts/validate-hacs-repo.sh`.

1. Use a clean Home Assistant test instance.
2. Copy this stage's `custom_components/zigbeelens/` directory so its contents
   land at
   `<home-assistant-config>/custom_components/zigbeelens/`. On HAOS the
   configuration root is normally `/config`. Do not copy the whole staged
   repository or merge files from different package versions.
3. Perform a full Home Assistant restart.
4. Open **Settings → Devices & services → Add integration → ZigbeeLens**.

Do not use the unsynchronized public satellite for this test.

Only one ZigbeeLens config entry/Core target is supported. The manifest declares
`single_config_entry: true`, with runtime guards retained.

The exact compatibility lanes are:

| Lane | Home Assistant | Python |
|------|----------------|--------|
| Minimum | `2025.1.0` | `3.12` |
| Current | `2026.7.3` | `3.14` |

Run `bash scripts/test-ha-integration-matrix.sh minimum` or
`bash scripts/test-ha-integration-matrix.sh current` from this staged
repository.

## Conditional public HACS installation

Public custom-repository installation is a future route only. Before restoring
it, the staged tree must match the intended satellite tree, the manifest/package
version must uniquely identify that tree, exact Home Assistant `2025.1.0` /
Python `3.12` and Home Assistant `2026.7.3` / Python `3.14` coverage must pass,
generated official HACS and hassfest validation must pass remotely on the
synchronized tree, and explicit publication authorization must be recorded.
Only after those gates close may an operator add
`https://github.com/@FUTURE_HACS_REPOSITORY@` as a HACS Integration
custom repository.

## Core URL examples

| Deployment | Typical URL |
|------------|-------------|
| Docker on LAN | `http://<docker-host-ip>:8377` |
| Docker Compose service | `http://zigbeelens:8377` |

The URL must be an exact HTTP(S) origin with no path, query, fragment, or
embedded credentials. Use `localhost` only when Home Assistant Core and
ZigbeeLens Core truly share a network namespace.

The Home Assistant add-on is deferred and is not part of this HACS release.
`http://localhost:8377` is not a portable add-on URL. Run standalone Core at a
reachable origin for HACS entities and the companion panel.

## Presentation paths

### Native companion summary (default)

The sidebar always opens on the **native companion panel**, a status and
launcher surface. It does not iframe Core automatically. HACS negotiates an
**exact companion decision contract**:

- `decision_contract_version = 2` only

When the contract is supported and the Dashboard decision payload is valid:

- the panel shows Core-provided investigation priorities under **What needs attention now**;
- Core priority labels, titles, and summaries are passed through unchanged;
- at most three priorities are shown, plus a restrained “+N more in the full ZigbeeLens dashboard” hint;
- factual counts include investigation priorities, data coverage warnings, active incidents, networks, devices, and unavailable devices;
- no separate Device Story, reason, coverage, action-group, or card-type wording table exists in HACS.

When the contract is missing, older, newer, or malformed — or the Dashboard
decision surfaces are missing/malformed — decision cards stay off softly. The
safe fallback shows connection and compatibility facts without inventing a
Health/Lens diagnosis.

Missing/malformed Core versions fail closed as **Unknown**, not Compatible.
Older, newer, and malformed Decision contracts and
missing/malformed exact-v2 Dashboard Decision data have distinct repair
guidance; payload-shape failure does not prescribe a Core upgrade.

### Opt-in embedded Core

**Try Embedded View** enters iframe mode when browser mixed-content rules allow
and Core allows the Home Assistant origin in its frame policy. HTTPS Home
Assistant cannot embed HTTP Core; HTTP Home Assistant may embed HTTPS Core.
**Back to Summary** always returns to the native panel, including when Core's
CSP prevents the iframe from loading.

**Open Full ZigbeeLens dashboard** opens the canonical Core UI in a new tab and
remains the reliable route to full evidence.

## Configure

Setup asks for the Core URL, optional API token, SSL verification (default
off), and whether to show the panel (default on). The polling interval defaults
to 60 seconds. The OptionsFlow behind **Configure** persists a selected
15–900-second interval and panel visibility, then Home Assistant performs one
effective reload.

Use **Reconfigure** to replace the Core URL, SSL setting, or API token. A Core
401 starts Home Assistant reauthentication. The token stays in Home Assistant's
server-side config-entry storage and is never placed in panel data, iframe URLs,
or dashboard links.

Standalone browser login for **Try Embedded View** / **Open Full Dashboard**
requires both Core `security.api_token` and `security.session_secret`.
Bearer-only Core deliberately leaves the browser UI locked.

## What this integration does

- Summary sensors and binary sensors for Home Assistant automations
- A native companion panel (contract-gated shared decisions when available)
- **Open Full ZigbeeLens dashboard** (Core in a new tab)
- Optional **Try Embedded View** when browser security allows
- Redacted diagnostics (including decision-contract version, availability, and Core compatibility)
- Repairs for Core reachability / collector / configuration issues
- Exact Core-local Home Assistant registry name/area enrichment

The full ZigbeeLens dashboard remains **canonical**.

Per-network entities are created at platform setup; reload the integration after
Core network changes, and manually remove stale unavailable registry entries
when needed. The panel/websocket summary is visible to every authenticated Home
Assistant user and includes the Core URL, network labels, counts, and priority
text.

## What it does not do

- Does **not** mutate Zigbee devices
- Does **not** publish MQTT or talk to Zigbee2MQTT
- Does **not** create per-priority or per-Device-Story entities; the documented
  overall/count decision summary entities are provided
- Does **not** add Zigbee control services, buttons, or switches
- Does **not** invent Decision Engine wording or severity colouring from aggregate counts
- Entities are summaries only — Core dashboard remains authoritative

## Enrichment safety

The integration reads Core diagnostic/configuration/Decision/capability data
and bounded device inventory. Its only write is the strict versioned HA
enrichment snapshot; explicit config-entry removal may call the exact clear.
HA names and areas supplement the preserved Zigbee2MQTT friendly name and never
act as identity. Final identity is exact `(network_id, ieee_address)`, with
ambiguous duplicate-IEEE candidates omitted.

A complete accepted empty snapshot clears enrichment. Unavailable HA
registries/inventory and transient failures send no replacement and retain the
last accepted snapshot. One manager owns initial sync, debounced official
registry events, bounded retry, forced 15-minute reconciliation, and unload
cleanup.

## Safety

Read-only bridge to Core.

## Upgrade or remove

For a local/staged update, stop Home Assistant, replace
`<home-assistant-config>/custom_components/zigbeelens` as one unit, and perform
a full restart. To remove the staged integration, delete its ZigbeeLens config
entry under **Settings → Devices & services**, stop Home Assistant, remove the
manually installed custom-component directory, and restart. HACS-managed
upgrade/removal applies only to a future synchronized, authorized public
artifact. Core and its SQLite data are not removed.

Issues: https://github.com/@SOURCE_REPOSITORY@/issues
